# Gentoo Optimizations

# The combination of xs, asm, orc, jit, threads, and kms represents a
# performance-oriented configuration that maximizes hardware utilization
# and system responsiveness. The asm, orc, and jit flags empower software to use
# hand-optimized assembly routines and just-in-time compilation, which
# significantly accelerates tasks like media processing and script execution. By
# including threads and kms, you ensure the system is optimized for multi-core
# parallelism and flicker-free, high-resolution graphics output via the kernel's
# display manager.
#
# TODO: removed seccom
# While you have explicitly excluded seccomp to prioritize stability and
# minimize overhead, this set of flags as a whole essentially forces your
# applications to run at the closest possible level to your underlying hardware,
# reducing software-induced latency.
*/* xs asm orc jit threads kms

# Make the GCC executable run faster when compiling other packages by building
# GCC itself using Profile-Guided Optimization (PGO) and Link-Time Optimization
# (LTO). This typically yields a 10% to 20% performance improvement in compile
# times.
sys-devel/gcc pgo lto

# PGO optimizes code blocks inside individual source files
app-shells/bash pgo
app-arch/xz-utils pgo
sys-devel/binutils pgo
dev-lang/python pgo

# native-extensions: This flag influences how certain interpreted language
# packages compile performance-sensitive subroutines into native binary code.
*/* native-extensions
